c-income UBI at the von Mises institute]\n* [http://igps.victoria.ac.nz/WelfareWorkingGroup/Downloads/Working%20papers/Treasury-A-Guaranteed-Minimum-Income-for-New-Zealand%20.PDF Treasury study in New Zealand 2010]\n* [https://newphysiocrats.org/platform/ The New Physiocratic League Platform]\n* [https://citizencapitalism.org Website for the book ''Citizen Capitalism'']\n* [http://www.queen-of-france.com/2011/11/new-world-government.html \"The Pre-Paid Wage\" of $20,000 per yr: supported by a property sales tax rate of 25%: written in 2011 by Therese Vaux de la Fontaine, The Capetian Queen of France]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aIL_Y9g7Tg0 Why we should give everyone a basic income | Rutger Bregman | TEDxMaastricht]. Video on [[YouTube]], provided by [[TED (conference)|TED]]. Published 21 October 2014.\n* [https://www.debateart.com/debates/86/universal-basic-income Universal basic income] Textual debate about UBI.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC8f0bqKU2-SyNSnA0EiVGfg/videos UBIVisuals] \u2013 Prominent statements on the UBI in America.\n\n{{-}}\n{{basic income}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Basic income| ]]\n[[Category:Income distribution]]\n[[Category:Labor relations]]\n[[Category:Market socialism]]\n[[Category:Political theories]]\n[[Category:Government aid programs]]\n", "name_user": "Ramosama", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basic_income"}
{"title_page": "J. A. Baker", "text_new": "'''John Alec Baker'''  (1926 \u2013 1987) was an English author, best known for ''The Peregrine,''<ref>{{cite journal|author=Zarin, Cynthia|authorlink=Cynthia Zarin|title=Time Out: The Beauty of J. A. Baker's \"The Peregrine\"|journal=The New Yorker|date=17 April 2017|url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-beauty-of-j-a-bakers-the-peregrine}}</ref> which won the [[Duff Cooper Prize]] in 1967.\n\n==''The Peregrine''==\n[[Robert Macfarlane (travel writer)|Robert Macfarlane]] deemed ''The Peregrine'' to be \"a masterpiece of twentieth-century non-fiction\" in his introduction to the New York Review Books edition of the book.<ref>''The Peregrine'' by J.A. Baker, Introduction by Robert Macfarlane, New York Review Books 2005, {{ISBN|9781590171332}}</ref> On the back jacket cover of the same edition, [[James Dickey]] states that the book \"transcends any 'nature writing' of our time,\" while [[Barry Lopez]] declares the book to be \"one of the most beautifully written, carefully observed and evocative wildlife accounts I have ever read.\" [[Werner Herzog]] called it the \"one book I would ask you to read if you want to make films,\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Werner Herzog's Masterclass|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RFqiy0l5qTg|website=Youtube}}</ref> and said elsewhere \"... it has prose of the caliber that we have not seen since [[Joseph Conrad]].\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Werner Herzog's Required Reading |url=http://www.openculture.com/2015/12/werner-herzog-lists-of-required-books-and-films.html}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, ''The Peregrine'' was included by the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]] in a list of 10 contenders<ref>{{cite web|title=AHRC Favourite Nature Books|url=http://www.ahrc.ac.uk/favouritenaturebooks/}}</ref> to find the UK's favourite book about nature. When the result was announced at the end of January on the [[BBC]] ''[[Winterwatch]]'' programme it did not make the top three. The poll was topped by ''Fingers in the Sparkle Jar'' by [[Chris Packham]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Chris Packham's Fingers in the Sparkle Jar voted UK's favorite nature book  |url=http://www.ahrc.ac.uk/newsevents/news/chris-packhams-fingers-in-the-sparkle-jar-voted-uks-favourite-nature-book1/}}</ref>\n\nThe book recounts a single year from October to April (probably of 1962/3) from the author's ten-year obsession with the [[Peregrine falcon|peregrines]] that wintered near his home in [[Chelmsford]], Essex in eastern England. The writing is lyrically charged throughout, as the author's role of diligent observer gives way to a personal transformation, as Baker becomes, in the words of James Dickey on the book's jacket cover, \"a fusion of man and bird.\"\n\nThe [[BBC]] published a recording of ''The Peregrine'' read by [[David Attenborough]] in December 2019.  It is available for a year at the BBC Radio 4 website. <ref>{{cite web|title= Radio 4 website.|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p07xhbdk}}</ref>\n\n==Other works and legacy==\n \nBaker's only other book is 1969's ''The Hill of Summer,'' a lyrical and somewhat visionary account of summer's progress across the wilder parts of southern England.  Though not as famous as ''The Peregrine,'' it enjoys much the same reputation for literary beauty and naturalist precision.\n\nIn 2011, Collins published a new edition of ''The Peregrine''<ref>''The Peregrine: The Hill of Summer & Diaries: The Complete Works of J.A. Baker'', Introduction by Mark Cocker & Edited by John Fanshawe, Collins 2011, {{ISBN|978-0-00-739590-3}}</ref> which also included ''The Hill of Summer'' and extracts from his diaries. The book includes an introduction by [[Mark Cocker]] and notes by John Fanshawe. Prior to this book, little was known about Baker's personal life but this has now changed. He was born on 6 August 1926, to engineering draughtsman Wilfred and his wife Pansy Baker,<ref>The Peregrine: 50th Anniversary Edition, J. A. Baker, Introduction (by Mark Cocker)</ref> and lived in Chelmsford. His secondary education was at [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Chelmsford]]. His books are based largely on his observations of birds in the Essex countryside especially in the area from Chelmsford to the coast. He was unable to drive (despite working for [[The Automobile Association]]) and travelled by bicycle. From around 1970 he suffered from severe [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and contracted cancer as a result of the drugs taken to alleviate the arthritis. He died on 26 December 1987.\n\nThe [[University of Essex]] holds items associated with Baker. These include his diaries,  drafts of his books, corrected proofs, correspondence and his optical equipment used when birdwatching. The archive was catalogued in 2016 by Hetty Saunders and is now open to all those interested in Baker's life and work.<ref>{{cite web|title= Launch of University of Essex J A Baker Archive |url=https://www1.essex.ac.uk/news/event.aspx?e_id=10628}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017 Little Toller Books published the first biography of Baker, entitled ''My House of Sky - The life and work of J A Baker'' by Hetty Saunders.<ref>''My House of Sky - The life and work of J. A. Baker'' by Hetty Saunders, Little Toller Books 2017, {{ISBN|978-1-908213-49-5}}</ref> In addition to the biography, the book includes a selection of Baker's poetry, an article about the J. A. Baker Archive by John Fanshawe, with photographs of some of the items, and a section of photographs of Baker Country taken by local photographer, Christopher Matthews. The preface to the book is by Robert Macfarlane.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* \n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, J.A.}}\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:People from Chelmsford]]\n[[Category:People educated at King Edward VI Grammar School, Chelmsford]]\n[[Category:English nature writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''John Alec Baker'''  (1926 \u2013 1987) was an English author, best known for ''The Peregrine,''<ref>{{cite journal|author=Zarin, Cynthia|authorlink=Cynthia Zarin|title=Time Out: The Beauty of J. A. Baker's \"The Peregrine\"|journal=The New Yorker|date=17 April 2017|url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/the-beauty-of-j-a-bakers-the-peregrine}}</ref> which won the [[Duff Cooper Prize]] in 1967.\n\n==The Peregrine==\n[[Robert Macfarlane (travel writer)|Robert Macfarlane]] deemed ''The Peregrine'' to be \"a masterpiece of twentieth-century non-fiction\" in his introduction to the New York Review Books edition of the book.<ref>''The Peregrine'' by J.A. Baker, Introduction by Robert Macfarlane, New York Review Books 2005, {{ISBN|9781590171332}}</ref> On the back jacket cover of the same edition, [[James Dickey]] states that the book \"transcends any 'nature writing' of our time,\" while [[Barry Lopez]] declares the book to be \"one of the most beautifully written, carefully observed and evocative wildlife accounts I have ever read.\" [[Werner Herzog]] called it the \"one book I would ask you to read if you want to make films,\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Werner Herzog's Masterclass|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RFqiy0l5qTg|website=Youtube}}</ref> and said elsewhere \"... it has prose of the caliber that we have not seen since [[Joseph Conrad]].\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Werner Herzog's Required Reading |url=http://www.openculture.com/2015/12/werner-herzog-lists-of-required-books-and-films.html}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, ''The Peregrine'' was included by the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]] in a list of 10 contenders<ref>{{cite web|title=AHRC Favourite Nature Books|url=http://www.ahrc.ac.uk/favouritenaturebooks/}}</ref> to find the UK's favourite book about nature. When the result was announced at the end of January on the [[BBC]] ''[[Winterwatch]]'' programme it did not make the top three. The poll was topped by ''Fingers in the Sparkle Jar'' by [[Chris Packham]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Chris Packham's Fingers in the Sparkle Jar voted UK's favorite nature book  |url=http://www.ahrc.ac.uk/newsevents/news/chris-packhams-fingers-in-the-sparkle-jar-voted-uks-favourite-nature-book1/}}</ref>\n\nThe book recounts a single year from October to April (probably of 1962/3) from the author's ten-year obsession with the [[Peregrine falcon|peregrines]] that wintered near his home in [[Chelmsford]], Essex in eastern England. The writing is lyrically charged throughout, as the author's role of diligent observer gives way to a personal transformation, as Baker becomes, in the words of James Dickey on the book's jacket cover, \"a fusion of man and bird.\"\n\nThe [[BBC]] published a recording of ''The Peregrine'' read by [[David Attenborough]] in December 2019.  It is available for a year at the BBC Radio 4 website. <ref>{{cite web|title= Radio 4 website.|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p07xhbdk}}</ref>\n\n==Other works and legacy==\n \nBaker's only other book is 1969's ''The Hill of Summer,'' a lyrical and somewhat visionary account of summer's progress across the wilder parts of southern England.  Though not as famous as ''The Peregrine,'' it enjoys much the same reputation for literary beauty and naturalist precision.\n\nIn 2011, Collins published a new edition of ''The Peregrine''<ref>''The Peregrine: The Hill of Summer & Diaries: The Complete Works of J.A. Baker'', Introduction by Mark Cocker & Edited by John Fanshawe, Collins 2011, {{ISBN|978-0-00-739590-3}}</ref> which also included ''The Hill of Summer'' and extracts from his diaries. The book includes an introduction by [[Mark Cocker]] and notes by John Fanshawe. Prior to this book, little was known about Baker's personal life but this has now changed. He was born on 6 August 1926, to engineering draughtsman Wilfred and his wife Pansy Baker,<ref>The Peregrine: 50th Anniversary Edition, J. A. Baker, Introduction (by Mark Cocker)</ref> and lived in Chelmsford. His secondary education was at [[King Edward VI Grammar School, Chelmsford]]. His books are based largely on his observations of birds in the Essex countryside especially in the area from Chelmsford to the coast. He was unable to drive (despite working for [[The Automobile Association]]) and travelled by bicycle. From around 1970 he suffered from severe [[rheumatoid arthritis]] and contracted cancer as a result of the drugs taken to alleviate the arthritis. He died on 26 December 1987.\n\nThe [[University of Essex]] holds items associated with Baker. These include his diaries,  drafts of his books, corrected proofs, correspondence and his optical equipment used when birdwatching. The archive was catalogued in 2016 by Hetty Saunders and is now open to all those interested in Baker's life and work.<ref>{{cite web|title= Launch of University of Essex J A Baker Archive |url=https://www1.essex.ac.uk/news/event.aspx?e_id=10628}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017 Little Toller Books published the first biography of Baker, entitled ''My House of Sky - The life and work of J A Baker'' by Hetty Saunders.<ref>''My House of Sky - The life and work of J. A. Baker'' by Hetty Saunders, Little Toller Books 2017, {{ISBN|978-1-908213-49-5}}</ref> In addition to the biography, the book includes a selection of Baker's poetry, an article about the J. A. Baker Archive by John Fanshawe, with photographs of some of the items, and a section of photographs of Baker Country taken by local photographer, Christopher Matthews. The preface to the book is by Robert Macfarlane.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* \n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, J.A.}}\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:People from Chelmsford]]\n[[Category:People educated at King Edward VI Grammar School, Chelmsford]]\n[[Category:English nature writers]]\n", "name_user": "Throughthemind", "