yo-ahn (cropped).png|150x150px]]\n| leader2            = [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]]\n| color2             = EF426F\n| party2             = [[United Future Party|United Future]]<br/>{{small|with [[Future Korea Party|Future Korea]]}}\n| leader_since2      = 17 February 2020\n| leaders_seat2      = [[Jongno-gu|Jongno]] {{small|(''defeated'')}}\n| last_election2     = 122 seats<br />{{small|(as [[Liberty Korea Party|Saenuri]])}}\n| seats2             = 103 {{small|(84 + 19)}}\n| seat_change2       = {{decrease}} 19\n| popular_vote2      = '''9,441,520'''\n| percentage2        = '''33.8%'''\n| swing2             = {{increase}} 0.3%\n<!-- Justice -->\n| image3             = [[File:Sim Sang-jung.jpg|150x150px]]\n| leader3            = [[Sim Sang-jung]]\n| party3             = Justice Party (South Korea)\n| leader_since3      = [[2019 Justice Party (South Korea) leadership election|13 July 2019]]\n| leaders_seat3      = [[Gyeonggi]]&nbsp;[[Goyang]]&nbsp;A\n| last_election3     = 6 seats\n| seats3             = 6\n| seat_change3       = {{steady}}\n| popular_vote3      = 2,697,956\n| percentage3        = 9.6%\n| swing3             = {{increase}} 2.4%\n<!-- People -->\n| image4             = [[File:Ahn Cheol-Soo cropped (cropped).jpg|150x150px]]\n| color4             = ff7417\n| leader4            = [[Ahn Cheol-soo]]\n| party4             = People Party (South Korea)\n| leader_since4      = 23 February 2020\n| leaders_seat4      = ''(Not standing)''\n| last_election4     = \u2013\n| seats4             = 3\n| seat_change4       = ''New''\n| popular_vote4      =  1,896,719\n| percentage4        =  6.8%\n| swing4             = ''New''\n<!-- Open Democratic -->\n| image5             = \n| leader5            = [[Lee Keun-shik]]\n| color5             = 003E98\n| party5             = [[Open Democratic Party|Open Democratic]]\n| leader_since5      = 8 March 2020\n| leaders_seat5      = ''(Not standing)''\n| last_election5     = \u2013\n| seats5             = 3\n| seat_change5       = ''New''\n| popular_vote5      = 1,512,763\n| percentage5        = 5.4%\n| swing5             = ''New''\n\n| title = Speaker\n| before_election = [[Moon Hee-sang]]\n| before_party = Democratic Party of Korea\n| posttitle = \n| after_election = \n| after_party = \n| map = \n| note = \n}}\n{{Politics of South Korea}}\n\n'''South Korea's 21st legislative elections''' were held on 15 April 2020. All 300 members of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]] were elected, 253 from [[first-past-the-post]] [[_South Korean Legislature Constituencies|constituencies]] and 47 from [[party-list proportional representation|proportional party lists]]. They were the first elections held under a new electoral system, which had been proposed by incumbent president [[Moon Jae-in]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\uc9c0\ubc29\uc120\uac70 \ub4dd\uc2e4 \uacc4\uc0b0\u2026 \ubbfc\uc8fc\ub2f9-\ud55c\uad6d\ub2f9, \uc811\uc810\uc5c6\ub294 \u2018\uac1c\ud5cc\u2019 \ub300\uce58|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=020&aid=0003117583|lang=kr|website=The Dong-a Ilbo|publisher=Naver|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref> The two largest parties, the liberal [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]] and the conservative [[United Future Party]], set up new [[satellite party|satellite parties]] to take advantage of the revised electoral system.\n\nThe Democratic Party and its satellite, the [[Together Citizens' Party]], won a [[landslide victory]], taking 180 of the 300 seats (60%) between them.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/south-korea-ruling-party-wins-election-landslide-200416000355845.html]</ref> The Democratic Party alone won 163 seats \u2014 the highest number by any party since 1960. This guarantees the ruling liberal alliance an [[absolute majority]] in the legislative chamber, and the [[Supermajority#South_Korea|three-fifths super-majority]] required to fast-track its procedures. The conservative alliance between the [[United Future Party]] and its satellite [[Future Korea Party]] won only 103 seats, the worst conservative result since 1960.\n\n==Electoral system==\n{{see also|Elections in South Korea}}\n\n===Previous system===\n300 members of the National Assembly were elected in the 2016 elections, of whom 253 (84%) were elected from [[_South Korean Legislature Constituencies|single-member constituencies]] on a first-past-the-post basis, and 47 (16%) from [[closed list|closed party lists]] through [[Party-list proportional representation|proportional representation]] (PR) by the [[largest remainder method|Hare quota largest remainder method]], in accordance with South Korea's Public Official Election Act.<ref>Article 189, subsection (3), Public Official Election Act, {{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/05_resourcecenter/02_01.jsp|title=Legislation & Judicial Decision|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> To win seats through proportional representation, parties needed to pass an [[election threshold]] of either 5 single-member districts or 3% of the total list vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/02_elections/01_04.jsp|title=Election Districts and Representation System|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Electoral reform process===\n\nAn election reform bill was introduced in February 2019, which would change the allocation of PR seats to a hybrid of the [[mixed-member proportional]] and [[Mixed Member Majoritarian|mixed member majoritarian]] systems (also known as the Additional Member System and Parallel Vote, respectively).<ref name=bill>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20191227000589|title=National Assembly passes electoral reform bill|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=27 December 2019|website=The Korea Herald|access-date=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe legislative process utilised the 85th Article of the National Assembly law, called the 'Fasttrack' system, which does not require agreement between all parties. This was opposed by the main opposition [[Liberty Korea Party]] and [[Bareunmirae Party]] member [[Yoo Seong-min]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hankyung.com/politics/article/2019042823491|title=\uc720\uc2b9\ubbfc \"\uc5ec\uc57c \ud569\uc758 \uc5c6\ub294 \uc120\uac70\ubc95 \uac1c\uc815\uc740 \ub2e4\uc218\uc758 \ud6a1\ud3ec\"|date=29 April 2019|website=hankyung.com|language=ko|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref> The decision by [[Sohn Hak-kyu]], leader of the Bareunmirae, to approve the Fasttrack, and his dismissal of his fellow standing committee member [[Oh Shin-hwan]], stirred legal controversy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hankyung.com/politics/article/201904249582Y|title=\uc624\uc2e0\ud658 \uc0ac\ubcf4\uc784 \uac00\ub2a5? \ubd88\uac00\ub2a5?\u2026'\uad6d\ud68c\ubc95 48\uc870' \uc5ec\uc57c \uc0c1\ubc18\ub41c \ud574\uc11d|date=24 April 2019|website=hankyung.com|language=ko|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hankookilbo.com/News/Read/201904241823354816|title=\uc624\uc2e0\ud658 \uc0ac\ubcf4\uc784 \uac00\ub2a5\ud560\uae4c\u2026 \uad6d\ud68c\ubc95 48\uc870 \uc5c7\uac08\ub9b0 \ud574\uc11d|date=24 April 2019|website=\ud55c\uad6d\uc77c\ubcf4|language=ko|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref> The Prosecution Service declared that Sohn's actions did not merit criminal charges.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.mt.co.kr/renew/view.html?no=2020010213173048488&type=outlink&ref=https://www.google.com|title=\uac80\ucc30 '\ud328\uc2a4\ud2b8\ud2b8\ub799 \ub3d9\ubb3c\uad6d\ud68c' \ud669\uad50\uc548\u00b7\ub098\uacbd\uc6d0 \ubd88\uad6c\uc18d \uae30\uc18c(\uc0c1\ubcf4)|last=MoneyToday|date=2 January 2020|website=m.mt.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Liberty Korea Party physically disrupted the National Assembly Secretariat in April 2019, to interrupt the Fastrack legal maneuver. The Prosecution Service then opened an investigation into the violence in the National Assembly, and possible violation of the National Assembly law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yna.co.kr/view/AKR20190426149700001|title=\ud328\uc2a4\ud2b8\ud2b8\ub799 \uadf9\ud55c\ucda9\ub3cc, '\uc721\ud0c4\uc804' \uc774\uc5b4 '\uace0\uc18c\uace0\ubc1c\uc804'\uc73c\ub85c \ube44\ud654|last=\ubc29\ud604\ub355|date=26 April 2019|website=\uc5f0\ud569\ub274\uc2a4|language=ko|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kim |first1=Bo-gyung |title=[KH Explains] What is behind political impasse, violence at National Assembly? |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20190429000715 |work=The Korean Herald |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20190909/97348169/1|title=\uac80\ucc30, \ud328\uc2a4\ud2b8\ud2b8\ub799 \uc9c1\uc811 \uc218\uc0ac\u2026\uc218\uc0ac\ub300\uc0c1 \uc758\uc6d0 109\uba85|date=9 September 2019|website=The Dong-a Ilbo|language=ko|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20190429000715|title=[KH Explains] What is behind political impasse, violence at National Assembly?|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=29 April 2019|website=The Korea Herald|access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref> Several leading members of the LKP were [[indicted]], including leader [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]] and then-floor leader [[Na Kyung-won]]. The criminal charges included violence and violation of order.<ref name=\":0\" /> Several Democratic Party members were also charged.{{update-inline}}<!-- so were any of them convicted? -->\n\nThe bill was passed on 27 December 2019, despite physical obstruction in the Assembly voting area by the Liberty Korea Party.<ref name=bill/>\n\n===New system===\n[[File:Electoral System composition of South Korea's National Assembly.svg|thumb|Red: 253, First-Past-the-Post<br />\nBlue: 30, Party-list proportional (compensatory)<br />\nGreen: 17, Party-list proportional (parallel)]]\nThe National Assembly continues to have 300 seats, with 253 constituency seats and 47 proportional representation seats, as in previous elections. However, 30 of the PR seats were assigned on the new compensatory basis, while 17 continue to use the old [[parallel voting]] method.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20191227000589|title=National Assembly passes electoral reform bill|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=27 December 2019|website=The Korea Herald|access-date=27 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191223004552315|title=(2nd LD) Opposition party launches filibuster against electoral reform bill|last=\uae40\uad11\ud0dc|date=23 December 2019|agency=Yonhap News Agency|access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the new system, the main opposition [[Liberty Korea Party]] set up a [[satellite party]] (called the [[Future Korea Party]]) to maximise the number of PR seats it would gain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191224005700315|title=Main opposition to set up satellite party for more proportional representation seats|last=\uae40\uc218\uc5f0|date=24 December 2019|agency=Yonhap News Agency|access-date=27 December 2019}}</ref> The [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]] responded by setting up their own satellite party, the [[Together Democratic Party]]. In both cases, the main party stood candidates only in the constituency seats, whilst the satellite party stood only in the PR lists. This meant that the satellite party would receive the maximum number of compensatory seats, regardless of how [[overhang seats|over-represented]] the parent parties were in the constituencies. Smaller parties did not set up satellites, because the advantage only appears if the party is over-represented in the constituencies.\n\n===Restrictions on candidates===\nCandidates for the National Assembly were required to pay a fee of {{Currency|amount=15000000|type=KRW|first=yes}} (US$14,000 as of December 2017), and under the [[National Security Act (South Korea)|National Security Act]] the Constitutional Court may block the registration of \"left-wing\", \"pro\u2013North Korean\" parties, though this provision has not affected recent elections.<ref name=\"SGI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sgi-network.org/2015/South_Korea/Quality_of_Democracy|title=South Korea|publisher=[[Sustainable Governance Indicators]]|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Date and process===\nThe 2020 election for the National Assembly was held on 15 April, in accordance with Article 34 of the Public Official Election Act, which specifies that Election Day for legislative elections is on \"the first Wednesday from the 50th day before the expiration of the National Assembly members term of office\".<ref>Article 34, Public Official Election Act, {{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/05_resourcecenter/02_01.jsp|title=Legislation & Judicial Decision|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> Eligible voters were required to be registered and at least 18 years old on the day of the election,<ref name=\"SGI\" /> and needed to show an approved form of identification at the [[polling place]]. Polls on Election Day were open from 6 a.m. to 6 p.m. [[Korea Standard Time]] (21:00\u201309:00 UTC, 14\u201315 April).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nec.go.kr/engvote_2013/04_news/04_01_voting.jsp|title=National Assembly elections: April 13, 2016|publisher=Republic of Korea National Election Commission|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince 2009, voters have been entitled to vote from overseas.<ref name=\"SGI\" /> Voters could also cast early votes at polling stations in Korea without prior notice.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lee|first=Rachel|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/04/116_202228.html|title=Early voting begins for general election|newspaper=[[The Korea Times]]|date=8 April 2016|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Parties and candidates==\n{{see also|List of political parties in South Korea}}\n \nBoth major parties split to take advantage of the new partial [[mixed-member proportional]] electoral system put in place since the prior elections, with the main party only running in the constituencies (all their seats being therefore counted as [[overhang seats]]), and the satellite party only running for the proportional bloc seats (all seats therefore being filled with party lists).<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 2 March 2020|title= \ucc3d\ub2f9\uc120\uc5b8\ubb38|url= http://platformparty.kr/?page_id=23|work= |location= |access-date= 17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe parties are sorted by their current number of seats (prior to the election).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Parties\n! Incumbent seats\n! Positioning and ideologies\n! Leader\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Democratic Party of Korea/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Democratic Party of Korea]]<br><small>[[Together Citizens' Party]]</small>\n| 120<br><small>8</small>\n| '''[[Centrism|Center]] to [[Centre-left politics|center-left]]'''<br>[[Liberalism]], [[Social Liberalism|Social liberalism]]\n| [[Lee Hae-chan]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{United Future Party/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[United Future Party]]<br><small>[[Future Korea Party]]</small>\n| 92<br><small>20</small>\n| '''[[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]]'''<br>[[National conservatism]], [[Economic liberalism]], [[Anti-communism]]\n| [[Hwang Kyo-ahn]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Party for People's Livelihoods/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Party for People's Livelihoods]]\n| 20\n| '''[[Centrism|Center]]'''<br>[[Reformism]], [[Liberalism]], [[Social conservatism]]\n| [[Kim Jung-hwa (politician)|Kim Jung-hwa]]<br>[[Yu Sung-yup]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Justice Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Justice Party (South Korea)|Justice Party]]\n| 6\n| '''[[Centre-left politics|Center-left]]'''<br>[[Social democracy]], [[Progressivism]]\n| [[Sim Sang-jung]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Our Republican Party/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Our Republican Party (2020)|Our Republican Party]]\n| 2\n| '''[[Far-right politics|Far-right]] <small>([[New Right (South Korea)|New Right]])</small>'''<br>[[Right-wing populism]], [[Social conservatism]], [[Ilminism]], Pro-[[Park Geun-hye|Park]]\n| [[Cho Won-jin]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Minjung Party/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Minjung Party]]\n| 1\n| '''[[Left-wing politics|Left-wing]]'''<br>[[Progressivism]]\n|''Collective leadership''\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:#F07D12\" | \n| [[Korea Economic Party]]\n| 1\n| '''[[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]]'''<br>[[Conservatism]]\n| [[Choi Jong-ho]]<br>[[Lee Eun-jae]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{People Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[People Party (South Korea)|People Party]]\n| 1\n| '''[[Centrism|Center]] to [[Centre-right politics|center-right]]'''<br>[[Liberalism]], [[Reformism]]\n| [[Ahn Cheol-soo]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Pro-Park New Party/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Pro-Park New Party]]\n| 1\n| '''[[Right-wing]] to [[Far-right politics|far-right]]'''<br>[[National conservatism]], [[Right-wing populism]], [[Anti-communism]], Pro-[[Park Geun-hye|Park]]\n| [[Hong Moon-jong]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:{{Open Democrats/meta/color}}\" | \n| [[Open Democrats]]\n| 1\n| '''[[Centrism|Center]] to [[Centre-left politics|center-left]]'''<br>[[Liberalism]], [[Social liberalism]]\n| [[Lee Keun-shik]]\n|-\n|}\n\nParties not represented in the current National Assembly but plan on running candidates include:\n\n* The [[Green Party Korea]] (\ub179\uc0c9\ub2f9), a [[green politics|green]] political party.\n* The [[Labor Party (South Korea)|Labor Party]] (\ub178\ub3d9\ub2f9), a [[democratic socialism|democratic socialist]] political party.\n* The [[:ko:\uc5ec\uc131\uc758\ub2f9|Women's Party]], a [[Radical feminism|feminist]] political party.\n* The [[:ko:\uae30\ubcf8\uc18c\ub4dd\ub2f9|Basic Income Party]], a single-issue party split from the [[Labor Party (South Korea)|Labor Party]] (\ub178\ub3d9\ub2f9) to campaign for [[universal basic income]].\n* [[Our Future|Future Party]], a youth-led center-left to left-wing political party founded in 2017, focusing more on youth voting, outreach, and campaigning.\n* [[National Revolutionary Dividends Party]], a [[Syncretic politics|third position]] populist and anti-corruption political party.\n\n==Opinion polls==\n{{Main|Opinion polling for the 2020 South Korean legislative election}}\n\n== Results ==\n<!-- Parties are by number of PR votes. The Democratic-Together Citizens pair, and the United Future-Future Korea pair should remain together in the table. -->\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:right\n|colspan=15 align=center|[[File:South Korea National Assembly 2020.svg]]\n|-\n!colspan=2 rowspan=2|Party\n!colspan=3|[[South Korean Legislature Constituencies|Constituency]]\n!colspan=5|Proportional\n!rowspan=2|Total<br>seats\n!rowspan=2|+/\u2013\n|-\n!Votes\n!%\n!Seats\n!Votes\n!%\n![[Mixed Member Majoritarian|M]]\n![[Mixed-member proportional representation|C]]\n!Total\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Democratic Party of Korea/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]] / [[Together Citizens' Party]]{{efn|Democratic Party in constituency seats and Together Citizens' Party in proportional seats}}||14,345,425||49.91||163||9,307,112||33.36||6 || 11||17||180||style=color:green|+57\n|-\n|bgcolor={{United Future Party/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[United Future Party]] / [[Future Korea Party]]{{efn|United Future Party in constituency seats and Future Korea Party in proportional seats}}||11,915,277||41.45||84||9,441,520||33.84|| 7|| 12||19||103||style=color:red|\u201319\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Justice Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Justice Party (South Korea)|Justice Party]]||487,519||1.69||1||2,697,956||9.67|| 2|| 3||5||6||0\n|-\n|bgcolor={{People Party (South Korea)/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[People Party (South Korea)|People Party]]||\u2013||\u2013||\u2013||1,896,71