{"title_page": "2009 World Cup of Pool", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Professional pairs nine-ball tournament, held September 2009}}\n{{Infobox pool tournament\n|tournament_name=\n|dates=\n|startdate=1\n|enddate=6 September 2009\n|venue=[[SM City North EDSA#The Annex (Annex 1)|The Annex]] of [[SM City North EDSA]]\n|city=[[Quezon City]]\n|country=[[Philippines]]\n|organisation=[[Matchroom Sport]]\n|format=[[Single elimination tournament]]\n|Total prize fund=$250,000\n|winners_share=$30,000 per player\n|highest_break=\n|defending_champion=\n|winner={{flagicon|Philippines}} B ([[Francisco Bustamante]] and [[Efren Reyes]])\n|runner_up={{flagicon|Germany}} ([[Ralf Souquet]] and [[Thorsten Hohmann]])\n|score=11&ndash;9\n|previous=[[2008 World Cup of Pool|2008]]\n|next=[[2010 World Cup of Pool|2010]]\n}}[[File:SM The Annex.jpg|thumb|The Annex of [[SM City North EDSA]], site of the 2009 World Cup of Pool.]]\n\nThe '''2009 World Cup of Pool''' was a professional [[pool (cue sports)|pool]] tournament played in the discipline of [[nine-ball]].  The event was the fourth [[World Cup of Pool]], a [[scotch doubles]] knockout championship representing national teams. The cup was played at [[SM City North EDSA#The Annex (Annex 1)|the Annex]] of [[SM City North EDSA]] in [[Quezon City]], Philippines from 1 to 6 September 2009. The Korean team of [[Ga Young Kim]] and [[Yun Mi Lim]] were the first all-female team to participate at the event. The tournament featured a prize fund of [[$]]250,000 with the winner receiving $60,000.\n\nThe defending champions were [[Rodney Morris]] and [[Shane Van Boening]] representing the USA. The team were defeated in the quarter-finals by the Chinese pair [[Fu Jian-bo]] and [[Li He-wen]] 5-9. The event was won by the Filipino team of [[Francisco Bustamante]] and [[Efren Reyes]], who defeated the German team of [[Ralf Souquet]] and [[Thorsten Hohmann]] in the final 11-9.\n\n==Tournament Overview==\n===Tournament Rules===\n*Winners' break.\n*Teammates take shots alternately.\n*Race to eight racks for matches prior to the quarterfinals.\n*Race to nine racks for matches from the quarterfinals to the semifinals.\n*Race to eleven racks for the Final.\n*Eighty-second shot clock for the shot immediately after the break, forty seconds for other shots.\n*In order for a break to be legal, two balls must pass over the head string.\n\n===Prize fund===\nPrize money for the event featured $250,000 with $60,000 being awarded to the winning team.<ref name=\"azbi_Part\" /> A breakdown of prize money is shown below:<ref name=\"dqU1D\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Stage !! Prize Money\n|-\n| Winner || [[United States dollar|$]]60,000\n|-\n| Runner-up || $30,000\n|-\n| Semi-final || $16,000\n|-\n| Quarter-final || $10,000\n|-\n| Second round || $5,000\n|-\n| First round || $3,000\n|-\n| Total || $250,000\n|-\n|}\n\n===Teams===\nParticipating nations for the event were announced on 31 July 2009, with 31 countries participating, two teams representing the host nation Philippines.<ref name=\"azbi_Worl\" /><ref name=\"pro9_2009\" /> The teams were announced on 14 August with all three prior winners of the competition participating.<ref name=\"azbi_Gian\" /> An all female team, representing Korea, competed at the event for the first time.<ref name=\"azbi_Gian\" /> The teams are listed below:<ref name=\"azbi_Gian\" /><ref name=\"pro9_Firs\" /><ref name=\"dqU1D\" />\n{{col-start}}{{col-break}}\n*Seeded teams:\n*#{{flag|USA}} ([[Rodney Morris]] and [[Shane Van Boening]])\n*#{{flag|Philippines}} A ([[Ronato Alcano]] and [[Dennis Orcollo]])\n*#{{flag|Germany}} ([[Ralf Souquet]] and [[Thorsten Hohmann]])\n*#{{flag|England}} ([[Darren Appleton]] and [[Imran Majid]])\n*#{{flag|Philippines}} B ([[Francisco Bustamante]] and [[Efren Reyes]])\n*#{{flag|Netherlands|name=Holland}} ([[Niels Feijen]] and [[Nick van den Berg]])\n*#{{flag|Chinese Taipei|name=Taiwan}} ([[Lai Chia-Hsiung]] and [[Yang Ching-shun]])\n*#{{flag|Finland}} ([[Mika Immonen]] and [[Markus Juva]])\n*#{{flag|China}} ([[Fu Jian-bo]] and [[Li He-wen]])\n*#{{flag|Poland}} ([[Rados\u0142aw Babica]] and [[Mateusz Sniegocki]])\n*#{{flag|Japan}} ([[Hayato Hijikata]] and [[Satoshi Kawabata]])\n*#{{flag|Italy}} ([[Bruno Muratore]] and [[Fabio Petroni]])\n*#{{flag|Spain}} ([[David Alcaide]] and [[Rafael Guzman]])\n*#{{flag|Canada}} ([[Tyler Edey]] and [[Jason Klatt]])\n*#{{flag|Russia}} ([[Ruslan Chinakhov]] and [[Konstantin Stepanov]])\n*#{{flag|India}} ([[Raj Hundal]] and [[Dharminder Singh Lilly]])\n{{col-break}}\n*Unseeded teams:\n**{{flag|Australia}} (Lou Condo and Greg Jenkins)\n**{{flag|Austria}} (Martin Kempter and [[Jasmin Ouschan]])\n**{{flag|Belgium}} (Pascal Budo and Serge Das)\n**{{flag|Croatia}} (Philipp Stojanovic and Ivica Putnik)\n**{{flag|Denmark}} (Kasper Kristoffersen and Bahram Lotfy)\n**{{flag|France}} (Stephan Cohen and Vincent Facquet)\n**{{flag|Hong Kong}} (Kenny Kwok and Lee Chenman)\n**{{flag|Indonesia}} (Muhammad Bewi Simanjuntak and Muhammad Zulfikri)\n**{{flag|South Korea|name=Korea}} ([[Ga-Young Kim]] and Yun-Mi Lim)\n**{{flag|Malaysia}} (Ibrahim Bin Amir and Lee Poh Soon)\n**{{flag|Malta}} ([[Alex Borg]] and [[Tony Drago]])\n**{{flag|Qatar}} (Bashar Hussain and Mohammed Ali Bin Ali)\n**{{flag|Singapore}} (Chan Keng Kwang and Toh Lian Han)\n**{{flag|Sweden}} ([[Marcus Chamat]] and [[Tom Storm (pool player)|Tom Storm]])\n**{{flag|Thailand}} (Nitiwat Kanjanasri and Surethep Phoochalam)\n**{{flag|Vietnam}} ([[Luong Chi Dung]] and [[Nguyen Thanh Nam]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Tournament Summary==\n===First round===\n*The all-female Korean team of [[Ga Young Kim]] and [[Yun Mi Lim]] is eliminated by the 2007 champions Chinese team of [[Li He-wen]] and [[Fu Jian-bo]].<ref name=\"CBN\" />\n*The [[Ronnie Alcano]]/[[Dennis Orcollo]] duo won after the upstart Thai team led by 5&ndash;4.<ref name=\"CBN\" />\n\n===Second round===\n*In a show of sportsmanship, Spanish [[David Alcaide]] admitted a foul to the referee that allowed the English team to pull away and win the match two racks later.<ref name=\"1wWrH\" />\n*The Filipino team of [[Efren Reyes]] and [[Francisco Bustamante]] took advantage of a call by the Filipina referee called a foul on the Italians after [[Bruno Muratori]]'s hair on his arm touched the cue ball.<ref name=\"784hs\" />\n\n===Semi-finals===\nIn the first semifinal, the match went to a hill-hill face-off. After the Chinese had a legal break at the final rack, Fu missed a two-ball carom on the corner pocket, that led to the run-out by the Filipino team of Reyes and Bustamante to advance to the final. In the other semifinal, the German team of [[Ralf Souquet]] and [[Thorsten Hohmann]] prevented an all-Filipino final with a 9&ndash;6 decision.<ref name=\"Final day\" />\n\n===Final===\nIn the final, the debut World Cup champions faced two former world champions in a race-to-11 affair. Germany won the lag, but the Philippines won the first three racks. The Germans caught up and even lead 5&ndash;3. The Philippines tied the match 6&ndash;all, then 16th rack became a long drawn-out safety match, with Reyes and Bustamante missing long shots.<ref name=\"azbi_Phil\" /> Souquet himself converted a long shot at the 9-ball to put the Germans up 8&ndash;6, but the Filipinos then reached the hill first when Souquet missed the 5-ball on the 20th rack. Reyes and Bustamante shook off earlier mistakes, with Reyes sinking the 9-ball to win the World Cup for the second time, the first time in World Cup history.<ref name=\"Final day\" />\n==Tournament bracket==\n{{32TeamBracket \n| RD1=Round 1<br />Race to 8\n| RD2=Round 2<br />Race to 8\n| RD3=Quarter-finals<br />Race to 9 \n| RD4=Semi-finals<br />Race to 9 \n| RD5=Final<br />Race to 11\n| team-width=130px\n\n| RD1-seed01=1\n| RD1-team01='''{{flag|USA}}'''\n| RD1-score01='''8'''\n| RD1-seed02=\n| RD1-team02={{flag|Malta}}\n| RD1-score02=7\n\n| RD1-seed03=16\n| RD1-team03={{flag|India}}\n| RD1-score